# Fix CLI-MK: Dashboard resolution fails on non-numeric IDs

## Issue
**Sentry Issue**: CLI-MK
**Error**: `ValidationError: No dashboard with title 'default-overview' found in 'pictrix'.`
**Irony**: The error message itself lists `default-overview  General` as an available dashboard.

## Root Cause

In `src/commands/dashboard/resolve.ts`, `resolveDashboardId()` handles dashboard references in two ways:
1. **All-digits** (line 123): Treated as a numeric ID, returned directly
2. **Everything else** (line 129): Matched only against `d.title` (case-insensitive)

Sentry's built-in dashboard has `id: "default-overview"` and `title: "General"`. The user passed `default-overview` — which is the dashboard's **ID/slug**, not its title. Since it's not all-digits, the code tries title matching, fails, and throws.

The error message format `${d.id}  ${d.title}` further confuses things — the user sees their input listed and thinks it should have matched.

## Fix

In `src/commands/dashboard/resolve.ts`, `resolveDashboardId()` function (lines 119-145):

### Change 1: Match by ID/slug in addition to title

Replace the single title match (line 129):
```typescript
const match = dashboards.find((d) => d.title.toLowerCase() === lowerRef);
```

With an ID-first match, falling back to title:
```typescript
// Match by ID/slug first (e.g. "default-overview"), then fall back to title
const match =
  dashboards.find((d) => d.id.toLowerCase() === lowerRef) ??
  dashboards.find((d) => d.title.toLowerCase() === lowerRef);
```

### Change 2: Improve error message clarity

Replace (lines 138-141):
```typescript
throw new ValidationError(
  `No dashboard with title '${ref}' found in '${orgSlug}'.\n\n` +
    `Available dashboards:\n${available}${suffix}`
);
```

With:
```typescript
throw new ValidationError(
  `No dashboard matching '${ref}' found in '${orgSlug}'.\n\n` +
    `Available dashboards (ID  Title):\n${available}${suffix}`
);
```

- Changed "with title" to "matching" since we now match both ID and title
- Added column labels "(ID  Title)" so users understand the listing format

## Testing

Add a test case in the dashboard resolve test file for slug-based resolution:
- Mock `listDashboards` to return `[{ id: "default-overview", title: "General" }]`
- Assert `resolveDashboardId(org, "default-overview")` returns `"default-overview"` (matched by ID)
- Assert `resolveDashboardId(org, "General")` returns `"default-overview"` (matched by title)
- Assert `resolveDashboardId(org, "nonexistent")` throws with improved error message

